##Hong Kong's fight against pandemic: cutting traffic to and from the mainland, scramble for mask vegetables

I-CAIJING

CAIJING magazine official Wechat. "CAIJING" magazine, sponsored by the China Securities Market Research Center, was first published in 1998, adhering to the news concept of "independence, exclusiveness and originality" , and is known for authoritative, impartial and professional reporting, it is a must-read publication for policy-makers, researchers and managers in the field of politics and economics.

Although the number of confirmed cases is not large, but because of SARS, hundreds of people in Block E of Amoy Gardens in Hong Kong fell ill, many Hong Kong people are emotional, they expect a series of preventive measures that have not yet landed can be effective

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
By Jiao Jian, special correspondent, Caijing, Hong Kong, China

Editor | Susie

Around 7:30 am on January 30, Zou Xin, who lives in the New Territories of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region of China, went out of her home and chose to take the MTR West Rail Line to a financial institution in Hong Kong's Central District to return to work, "The subway is faster than the bus, which reduces contact time with outsiders. "

This is already one day behind the start of the workday on the fifth day of the Lunar New Year (January 29) . When to return to work is a hot topic among many workers in the HKSAR due to the holiday season and the spread of COVID-19 pneumonia. On January 28, the government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region of China announced that all civil servants would be allowed to work from home from January 29 to February 2, except for emergency and essential public services. Relevant arrangements for the private sector have also been put in place.

According to the notice issued by the Human Resources Department of Ms. Zou's organization in the previous few days, in addition to the one-day delay in starting work for all employees and the implementation of the staggered rush hour system (arriving half an hour late and leaving half an hour late) , workers who have visited mainland China during the Spring Festival holiday can postpone it for much longer.

As of 10:00 am on January 30, the latest statistics show that the number of confirmed cases in COVID-19 is 10, with no deaths and no cured cases of discharge.

Reducing cross-border mobility is not easy

On January 28, China's Chief Executive of Hong Kong Carrie Lam announced a total of seven measures to prevent the spread of the disease, this includes arranging for Hong Kong residents stranded in Hubei to return to Hong Kong, charging all non-eligible persons for hospital fees, and collecting protective products such as face masks and hand sanitizer from around the world.

She said at a press conference on the same day that the main means of controlling the outbreak was to reduce the cross-border movement of people between the mainland and Hong Kong. After co-ordination, the mainland will first stop issuing "freedom trip" visas to 49 cities.

"The measures will inevitably cause inconvenience to people travelling between the mainland and Hong Kong, but they are an important part of the epidemic prevention work and we hope for understanding, " Lin zhengyuee said.

In accordance with the relevant arrangements, the HKSAR government will significantly reduce the air, land and sea services between the two places, including the suspension of all services of the Hong Kong section of the West Guryong Station Express rail link and the hung hom Intercity Through Train, and the halving of mainland flights to Hong Kong, temporary suspension of cross-boundary Ferry Services at Tsim Sha Tsui Hong Kong China Ferry Terminal and Tuen Mun Pier and reduction of cross-boundary bus trips. In addition, the government will suspend passenger services at some control points, including the Xrl West Kowloon Station Control Point, the Hung Hom Station Boundary Control Point, the Sha Tau Kok Control Point and the Man Kam To Control Point. Cargo services will not be affected.

This is the latest escalation of the response measures following the launch of the measures at a meeting of the steering committee and Command Centre of the COVID-19 on 26 January in Hong Kong.

In accordance with the relevant arrangements of the meeting, starting from 00:00 on January 27, all residents of Hubei Province, except Hong Kong residents, and anyone who has visited Hubei Province in the past 14 days will no longer be allowed to enter the HKSAR, until further notice. To facilitate the implementation of the above measures, the self-service kiosks at Boundary Control points are open to Hong Kong residents only. All non-hong Kong residents are required to use the general immigration counters for immigration clearance.

In response to Hong Kong society's recent call for a "total closure of Immigration Checkpoints" , Carrie Lam also reiterated at a news conference on January 28 that the implications were "very far-reaching" , it will also make it temporarily impossible for many Hong Kong people who are still outside Hong Kong to return to Hong Kong.

The reporter from Caijing learned that about half of the people from the mainland of China who come to the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region now come to Hong Kong on "freedom tour" endorsements, and about 20 percent come as tour groups. The rest come to Hong Kong for business, visiting relatives or taking care of relatives and friends.

"although it is still claimed that the current measures have minimised unnecessary travel between the two places. But whether the chances of entry and exit will be further reduced due to public opinion in Hong Kong and other reasons, I am not sure,"a mainland resident in Hong Kong holding a visa for family visits told Caijing, "visitors can stay in Hong Kong for up to 90 days on each visa and hopefully by then the epidemic will have been contained. "

Masks are hard to buy, creating a "shortage economy"

According to the information released by the Hong Kong SAR government of China, the financial resources of the SAR government are not a problem, but the supply of materials is relatively tight. The Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) government has scoured the world for related materials, including face masks and hand sanitizers, with a view to ensuring adequate supply in the market as soon as possible.

The positive effects of these measures, which have yet to be fully implemented, have yet to take effect, as the SARS outbreak in block e of Amoy Gardens in Hong Kong is still fresh in the minds of many Hong Kong people and the mood of many Hong Kong people has become tense.

According to Caijing reporter's observation in Mong Kok, the New Territories and other areas around the Spring Festival: Before the Spring Festival, although there was news of disease, but the supply of masks, disinfectant fire wine (alcohol) and other materials still appeared normal, and wearing masks on the streets is not common; Since the first day of the Lunar New Year, the shortage has started to worsen, with nine out of ten people wearing masks on the streets.

Take the sales of face masks in the vicinity of the buildings where CAIJING reporters live in Hong Kong. For example, a white japanese-made face mask against pollen and viruses has been raised to 180 yuan (50 Hong Kong dollars) per box by the third day of the year. There is still a lot of stock on the shelves of pharmacies By am the next day, adult masks had been sold out, leaving only children's masks. By PM the next day, a number of shops had put out "masks, fire wine, disinfectant all clean" corrugated cardboard.

The boss of a pharmacy in Mong Kok, Hong Kong, said: Last week when the price of goods to low, a box of retail price of 120 yuan is still profitable. On the 28th, when I wanted to order from Japanese manufacturers, the purchase price went up more than 10 times, plus freight, Spring Festival labor and shop rent, each box will go up to more than 1,000 yuan at any time

The situation in the supermarket chain is not optimistic: On January 29 and 30, there were long queues in front of a number of major grocery stores in Hong Kong, including Watson's and Guardian's. Some stores even had "snake-hunting cake" (standing in a circle)  In front of a shop, there are signs on the shutters saying Hong Kong is out of stock, but there are still many people lining up to "try their luck" . In a supermarket, which claims to have bought from Thailand, because the stock was quickly sold out, there were also incidents where the boss had to be shut down.

Along with the face mask shortage appears, is the vegetable and so on related daily life food's price also to rise. With a well-developed retail network, most Hong Kong families do not have the habit of stocking up on food items such as fruits, vegetables and meat during the Lunar New Year.

Take the PEA seedlings, for example. At the start of the New Year, the price of about forty per half-catty (16 taels per catty in Hong Kong) had doubled compared with normal days, but it was still thought to be a factor of the Spring Festival. Subsequently, daily vegetables such as Chinese Kale also rose from 18 yuan / 2 Jin to 20 yuan / Jin on the fifth day of the Lunar New Year, allowing more and more Hong Kong people to feel the impact of the "shortage economy" brought about by the epidemic.

"farmers still grow vegetables in the New Territories and other places, and with convenient transportation to Shenzhen, prices have only gone up in the past few days. In Hong Kong Island, there are only Shangchao communities where hundreds of yuan per catty of vegetables have to be snatched, " Zou said of his colleagues.

Along with the face mask shortage, there are also offline chain stores and other sales networks began to promote their online mall services. But take the supermarket chain, which claims to be able to order services such as face masks online but has been crippled for a long time by customers who weren't prepared for the site's affordability There are also bookshops to inform readers: for the fight against disease, epidemic hygiene supplies and health book promotion. But its merchandise does not have the mask, but only the environmental protection disinfection deodorizes the spray, the anti-virus carries the small hanging bag and so on.

The shortage of face masks has also been accompanied by increasing pressure on Hong Kong's health and anti-epidemic services. Affected by factors such as the relative lack of up-to-standard protective equipment, there have been reports from time to time that Hong kong-related personnel have applied for leave. There is also concern about the increasing reuse of face masks in Hong Kong, where they are hard to find, and the rising incidence of counterfeits.

In response to enquiries on increasing the supply of face masks, a spokesman for the commerce and Economic Bureau of the Government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region of China said: The government has been communicating with the mainland authorities, such as following up on individual batches of government procurement through co-operation between the two customs administrations, calls on trade representatives to provide specific information to the government for follow-up actions in case of procurement and customs clearance problems in respect of individual batches, and the Customs and Excise Department to step up inspections in three areas, namely consumer goods safety, trade marks and trade descriptions, such as origin, prevent illegal sales.

"The current situation in Hong Kong is as complicated as the epidemic... if the authorities mishandle it, it could set off another 'perfect storm' . The government needs to take more concrete actions to calm people's minds, ease the shortage of supplies, manage psychological expectations, and try to channel medical discontent... so that the public will have confidence that even the supply of face masks is not good enough to keep people calm." An editorial in Hong Kong called for.

More Hong Kongers are reminded of Betty Tung, the wife of former chief executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region of China Tung Chee Hwa, during a visit to the Lower Ngau Tau Kok (II) Estate during the SARS epidemic in 2003, she reminded the elderly to observe good personal hygiene: "Pray, pray, pray, wash your hands and wash your hands (remember, remember, wash your hands and wash your hands) . "

(Wennei Zou Xin is a pseudonym)
